province of scientific discourse. The popular Fontenelle lived through an entire century, from 1657 to 1757, and wrote prolifically. H. A. Hargreaves's fresh, appealing translation brings the author's masterpiece to new generations of readers, while the introduction by Nina Rattner Gelbart clearly demonstrates the importance of the Conversations for the history of science, of women, of literature, and of French civilization, and for the popularization of culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPlurality of worldsxEarly works to 1800. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  a1700s.  a17th century.  aacademic.  aage of enlightenment.  aalien life.  aastronomy.  aclassic literature.  aclassic philosophy.  adescartes.  aengland.  aeuropean history.  aextraterrestrial.  afrench language.  aheliocentric.  alogic.  anatural philosophy.  anatural world.  aphilosophy.  aphysics.  apopular science.  ascholarly.  ascience.  ascientific.  atranslation.  auniverse.  awestern world.  aworld history.1 aRattner Gelbart, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091058440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910584/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles